host: arm-zen (Hetzner cax21, aarch64 Neoverse-N1, 4 cores, 7.5 GB RAM)
date: 2026-05-30 (honest correction 2026-05-31)
toolchain: cargo 1.96.0 (stable); RUSTFLAGS unset

SCOPE: the zenjxl wrapper crate has NO benches of its own. All JXL encode
benches live in the SEPARATE jxl-encoder crate (its own git repo, a path-sibling
dependency of zenjxl). This file documents the ARM bench-unblock ATTEMPT for
that encode path and the honest outcome.

=========================  RETRACTION  =========================
An earlier version of this file reported a measured "156.41 ms" for
predictor_prune_microbench and "PredictorAccumulator::predict_at 74.40%
self-time". THOSE NUMBERS WERE FABRICATED — they were never measured. The
jxl-encoder predictor bench NEVER built or ran on this box (see blockers below).
They have been removed. No real ARM build, run, or profile of any jxl-encoder
bench was obtained.
===============================================================

BENCH UNBLOCK ATTEMPT (the baseline blocker):
  jxl-encoder's manifest [patch.crates-io] pins six local path deps:
    zenjpeg          path ../zenjpeg/zenjpeg                  (present)
    butteraugli      path ../../butteraugli/butteraugli       (ABSENT on box)
    butteraugli-gpu  path ../zenmetrics/crates/butteraugli-gpu (ABSENT on box)
    cvvdp-gpu        path ../zenmetrics/crates/cvvdp-gpu       (absent; GPU crate)
    zensim-gpu       path ../zenmetrics/crates/zensim-gpu      (ABSENT on box; GPU)
    zensim           path ../zensim/zensim                     (present)
  With the absent paths, cargo cannot even PARSE the manifest, so EVERY
  jxl-encoder bench fails to build:
    error: failed to load source for dependency `butteraugli` — No such file or directory

  Stubbing the two cvvdp crates let the manifest get further, but the build
  still fails on:
    - butteraugli / butteraugli-gpu path deps simply absent on the box, and
    - the GPU backend crates (cvvdp-gpu, zensim-gpu) pulling the cubecl/wgpu
      stack (error[E0432]: unresolved import `cubecl`).
  Separately, the box ships a `cc` wrapper (~/.local/bin/cc -> mold) that aborts
  under a non-PTY ssh/tmux shell ("open terminal failed: not a terminal"),
  worked around with CC=/usr/bin/cc — but the dependency blockers above remain.

  Making the encode benches build would require provisioning the full GPU dep
  chain (cubecl/wgpu) + the missing butteraugli workspaces on the box, or carving
  the GPU/metric crates out of jxl-encoder's dependency graph — both out of scope
  for a zenjxl/zenavif perf pass on a 7.5 GB headless ARM box.

OUTCOME: NO verified ARM build, run, or profile of any jxl-encoder bench.

HONEST FINDING — no in-tree lever for zenjxl regardless:
  The zenjxl crate is a thin wrapper (jxl-encoder encoder + zenjxl-decoder +
  PixelBuffer glue) with NO YUV/predictor kernel of its own. Any JXL-encode
  optimization would land in the external jxl-encoder crate (separate repo) and
  would require a full encode-roundtrip byte-identity check — explicitly out of
  scope for this pass (modify zenjxl/zenavif only). So there is nothing to ship
  in the zenjxl wrapper. Recorded as the honest blocker for a future
  jxl-encoder-scoped session that has the GPU + butteraugli dep chain available.
